        "body": "### **What You'll Need:**\n*   A cold milk pitcher\n*   Cold milk (whole milk is easiest for beginners)\n*   An espresso machine with a steam wand\n*   A damp cloth for cleaning\n\n### **The Process:**\n1.  **Purge:** Point the steam wand over the drip tray and turn it on for a few seconds to purge any condensed water.\n2.  **Position:** Submerge the tip of the steam wand just below the surface of the milk, slightly off-center in the pitcher. Tilt the pitcher slightly.\n3.  **Stretch (Aerate):** Turn the steam wand on to full power. You should hear a gentle 'Tsss-Tsss' sound, like paper tearing. This introduces air, creating foam. Only stretch for a few seconds until the milk volume increases by about 20-30% and the pitcher feels lukewarm.\n4.  **Texture (Emulsify):** Raise the pitcher slightly to submerge the wand deeper into the milk. Position the wand to create a whirlpool or vortex. This breaks down large bubbles and textures the milk into a silky, uniform microfoam. \n5.  **Heat:** Continue the whirlpool until the pitcher is hot to the touch (around 140-150°F / 60-65°C). Don't overheat, as this will scald the milk and ruin the flavour and texture.\n6.  **Stop & Clean:** Turn off the steam, remove the wand, and immediately wipe it with your damp cloth. Purge the wand again to clear any milk from the inside.\n7.  **Finish:** Gently tap the pitcher on the counter to remove any large bubbles and swirl the milk to keep it integrated and glossy. It should look like wet paint. Now you're ready to pour!"
